76561197993197707,Recommended,313080,16421044,"Posted: 15 June, 2015",all,ribbakylling,"A good game that with a little more effort could have been a great game. I've currently played 15 out of 20 maps.The good:- Good game mechanics. Hold up hostages, disabling camera feeds, line of sight, fog of war.- Nice graphics that combined with the music, suits the game very well.- Nice map design that combined with the game mechanics offers different approaches to reach your goals.- A lot of potential if the developers decides to improve the game or make a sequel.The bad:- The UI is lacking. Too easy to make mistakes- The AI is lacking. The NPC are too naive- The game is too easy.The ugly:- Others have experienced game crashes and I've sadly exprienced that a couple of times myself.- Some NPC are too (and unrealistically) trigger happy. The police chief at the impound started shooting my goons that had stood idle beside the van during the whole mission. He never saw the one goon that had been active and who also was the guy that ""unlocked"" the chief (I hid behind the door when I unlocked the southern door). I just ran outside and started shooting like a maniac. So that was police brutality at it's worst.As I said, this is a good game that could have been great. Even if the game mechanics is good, the game itself is just too easy. When you've gotten the basic and you have hired 1-2 more goons, found a guards uniform, you will, with a little patient, most likely run through most of the missions without much drama and no collateral damage. Basically, you send the guy in dress as a guard, and he will get you all the keys and cut of the camera feed without any problems. And then it is pretty much straight forward for the rest of your goons. You find yourself a room where you can lock off all exits (and make sure that it doesn't have a phone inside). And then you just ""invite"" one after another of the guards/civilians to that room.Much of the problems is that the NPC, especially the guards, are too naive. Other problems is that the guards don't try to fix the missing camera feeds.So what I would have liked to see regarding this is:- Guards try to fix the camera feeds. And if they cannot fix it, they become a lot more alert.- The guards communicate with each other for instance, via wire less (walkie talkie). So if the see something suspicious like a broken window, the call over other guards and they conduct a search. Also, they have com-checks now and again. So if you have lock guard A inside a room and guard B calls out for guard A and does not get an answerer, he will conduct a search.- More random behavior from NPC. For instance a guard get bored standing/patrolling, so I go to chat with colleague or goes to the kitchen to make a snack or go out for a smoke.- Different skill level on the guards. You can have one slacker who don't care if he saw something suspicious, others are extremely professional. And maybe having somebody that is completely paranoid.- random behavior when you hold up an NPC. For instance that some NPC can panic and try to run off.This is not part of the review, but more on how I would have liked to the game to be.I would have liked to see a more complex campaign where the police will investigate your heist. Basically, your goons can leave evidence during a heist which may increase the chances for the police to find you. For instance if you get caught on the camera, if you don't get the tape containing that recording, the police will know how your goon look like. NPC can become witnesses if they see your face. You can leave fingerprints at crime scene. So to counter this, you can wear masks and gloves. But using this when you are only gathering intel, it will increase the rate of suspicion by the NCP's. Also, there should be a notoritey level, so the more aggressive you are, the more public wants your arrest, and hence, more resources will be put into trying to solve who is behind these heites.Also it would have been fun if the game focused more on gathering intel before a heist. For instance you must have contacts to get the blueprint of buildings. Without these blueprint, the layout will be covered in the fog of war. Also you should be able to buy more intel, for instance how many guards there is at duty, how professional they and so on.And of course, it would have been cool having some RPG elements on your crew, learning skill and so on.And if all the above was include, it would the be put together with a sandbox career mode were you can include fan made maps to, and the ""plot"" is just to ""earn"" as much as you can until you either get caught or until you decide to retire. A little bit like Pirates. And this would also require a time-line where new technology becomes available both for you and the police (DNA for instance).And if you get caught, it would have been cool with a some prison break maps so you can arrange an earlier release. And if you don't decide to escape, you also can continue your career after you've served your time, if your health allows it.And what to do with the loot? Well, buy a lot of cool stuff, a mansion, a yacht and so on.Multiplayer would also be pretty awesome."
,Recommended,313080,12113213,"Posted: 15 September, 2014",all,Iron,"My suggestion: Buy this. You.will.not.regret.it.When I played ""The Masterplan"" for the first time, it blew me away to what extent it was uncomparable to anything else I've experienced before. At first glance you might be intrigued to draw a reference to Hotline Miami and honestly, this is the best thing that could happen to this game. While it presents itself in a familiar, established style, the game-mechanics itself are so one-of-kind, that it just draws you into this form of - I call it - ""new"" nostalgia, being reminded in a pleasant way of various, well-recieved games, such as Payday 1+2, Doorbreakers with its similiar top-down view and pace, Monaco with its different classes but by far not as arcadish and thought-out and finally a stylish, fitting gore which is reminiscent of the gruesomeness from the legendary Hotline Miami (of course by far not the same amount). And then again, it's a game of its own, which utilizes these known gameplay-mechanics in a different manner.For me personally, the cherry on the cake, is the amount of choice it provides you with. You will always find yourself polishing your approach to a mission which fits your preference the best and honestly, if this game pulls off to show this many alternatives to finish a level on the small maps included in the Early Access, I can only imagine how far this will reach out when the game hits release.Sure, there isn't very much to do at the moment but to replay the same levels and I'd understand, if you want to wait for more updates before your purchase.Personally though, the developer had it easy to convince me. Subjectively: Hot favourite for the best indie game of this year.You might ask yourself: Why didn't you play it more then?My answer: I don't want to spoil it for me too hard - I will play every update, see what's new, how it handles.Hope that makes sense to you. Buy it, if you're not short on money - 10€ is the same as getting it for free."
