,Recommended,313080,19992828,"Posted: 27 December, 2015",all,Kunovega,"Funny storyline, interesting setup. The gameplay is more of a puzzle/planning game with some very minor tactical elements. If you are looking for depth of action, look elsewhere.The downsides are really all in the mechanics though, a lot of the games difficulty comes from unresponsive controls and the clunky interface that doesn't do what you want it to do ""in the moment"", leaving you frustrated when one of your goons runs off and trys to circle around the building when what you wanted him to run over and do was directly in front of him but some stray box told him to go the long way.Also of interest is the metagame style used here where you evolve your crew and its tools between missions (or by going back and redoing missions to perfect them) which should in theory make every play through unique. Unfortunately there's not alot of depth to this either and the customization ends up coming down to generic thugs with random names and sometimes just redoing missions over again to get the money you need to finance a tool you need for the next mission.There's a lot to like in this clever little strategy/puzzle game, but it's also pretty unpolished and it's not terribly long. Unfortunately it also started to glitch and hiccup. During the pause screen (which is like a bullet time where you set up a series of moves) the game would often hiccup (pause within a pause) and not actually accept your input commands. And since its not actually stopping the action you get to watch in slow motion as your goons don't obey your detailed commands. (And than trying to reclick on the person you need when there's 5 of them overlapping to redo a command sequence that was multistepped is an excercise in frustration)...I wish I could write a glowing review for this game, the core elements are there it's just not quite perfected and it's probably never going to be.In the end I would still recomend the game but only on two conditions:1. you can tolerate some frustration in your puzzle interfaces2. get it on sale, I don't regret spending $5 on it, but I'd be pretty♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥off if I'd spent $20I'd kill for a less buggy version of the game or a ""pause while planning"" that isn't in glitchy slow motion, that would have been worth $20 instead of $5.Anyway if you played cops & robbers as a kid and were always the robbers, you'll probably find something to like in this game if you pick it up on sale."
